WEBVTT

1
00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:03.434
You seen commercials for
indigestion drugs? Pepcid AC.

2
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:04.794
Tagamet HB?

3
00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:06.439
Country's sick to their stomachs.

4
00:00:06.600 --> 00:00:09.558
You know you're supposed to take
these things before you get sick?

5
00:00:09.720 --> 00:00:11.392
- What is this. a bit?
- No.

6
00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:13.915
- Because I'm not in the mood.
- We're just talking.

7
00:00:14.080 --> 00:00:16.196
Is this not the greatest
marketing ploy ever?

8
00:00:16.360 --> 00:00:18.271
If you feel good.
you're supposed to take one.

9
00:00:18.440 --> 00:00:19.793
I know that tone. This is a bit.

10
00:00:19.960 --> 00:00:23.077
They've opened a whole new market.
Medication for the well.

11
00:00:23.240 --> 00:00:26.073
All right. Are you done
with your little amusement?

12
00:00:26.240 --> 00:00:27.673
Then you admit it was amusing?

13
00:00:27.840 --> 00:00:30.673
It was okay. But move the
"medication for the well" to the front...

14
00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:32.319
...and hit the word "good" harder.

15
00:00:32.480 --> 00:00:34.277
Great. Thanks.

16
00:00:40.040 --> 00:00:42.998
So your firm designed
all the furniture in here?

17
00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:44.991
Well. we manufacture it.

18
00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:47.196
The original designs
are by Karl Farbman.

19
00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:49.112
Oh. Farbman.

20
00:00:49.280 --> 00:00:51.953
- Do you know Farbman?
- Love Farbman.

21
00:00:52.240 --> 00:00:55.232
Most people go their whole lives
without sitting in a Farbman.

22
00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:57.630
Well. if you call that living.

23
00:01:00.920 --> 00:01:03.878
Wouldn't it be great if
Farbman designed shoes?

24
00:01:04.040 --> 00:01:07.794
Brett? Don't you think
that would be great? Brett?

25
00:01:07.960 --> 00:01:09.996
After the song. babe.

26
00:01:11.280 --> 00:01:12.918
This song.

27
00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:19.598
So when do I meet this jerk?

28
00:01:19.760 --> 00:01:22.991
He's not a jerk. Jer.
He only works with Karl Farbman.

29
00:01:23.160 --> 00:01:25.116
- Who?
- I don't know. Some designer.

30
00:01:25.280 --> 00:01:27.669
Anyway. Brett
is so generous and sensitive.

31
00:01:27.840 --> 00:01:30.035
Last night he was moved
just listening to a song.

32
00:01:30.200 --> 00:01:31.599
- What song?
- "Desperado."

33
00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:33.637
"Desperado"?
And you're still dating him?

34
00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:35.677
I'll tell you who sounds
a little desperado.

35
00:01:37.200 --> 00:01:39.031
See that salesman
twirling that umbrella?

36
00:01:39.200 --> 00:01:41.794
- I invented that.
- That had to be invented?

37
00:01:41.960 --> 00:01:44.076
When I started out as a comedian.
I sold umbrellas.

38
00:01:44.240 --> 00:01:47.676
It was my idea to twirl it
to attract customers.

39
00:01:47.840 --> 00:01:51.469
Oh. really? Well. why don't
we ask him about it?

40
00:01:51.880 --> 00:01:53.871
- Elaine.
- Excuse me.

41
00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:55.393
Hey. how you doing?

42
00:01:55.560 --> 00:01:59.439
My friend here says that he invented
that little twirl you're doing.

43
00:01:59.600 --> 00:02:02.068
Elaine. please.
it was a long time ago.

44
00:02:02.240 --> 00:02:03.992
The man doesn't want
a history lesson.

45
00:02:04.160 --> 00:02:06.037
Teddy Padilac
came up with this twirl.

46
00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:08.193
I know Teddy Padilac.

47
00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:10.590
I worked with him on 48th and Sixth.

48
00:02:10.760 --> 00:02:12.193
That's where he come up with it.

49
00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:15.079
- In his dreams.
- All right. Can we go?

50
00:02:15.240 --> 00:02:18.949
By the way. you're doing it too fast.
You'll disorient the customers.

51
00:02:21.960 --> 00:02:24.758
It's the twirling that dazzles the eye.

52
00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:27.431
I find it disorienting.

53
00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:29.079
Who buys an umbrella anyway?

54
00:02:29.240 --> 00:02:32.437
You can get them for free
in the coffee shop in the metal cans.

55
00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:34.750
Those belong to people.

56
00:02:38.200 --> 00:02:42.113
Hey. Well. this was
downstairs for you.

57
00:02:42.280 --> 00:02:43.838
Oh. no. not more checks.

58
00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.070
They're coming in faster
than I can sign them.

59
00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:47.719
- What checks?
- Oh. you didn't hear?

60
00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:49.677
Jerry's a big star in Japan.

61
00:02:49.880 --> 00:02:51.518
Don't know why.
There's a clip of me...

62
00:02:51.680 --> 00:02:54.148
...in the credits of some
Japanese comedy.

63
00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:56.470
Yeah. The Super Terrific Happy Hour.

64
00:02:57.480 --> 00:03:00.392
They run it all the time. I'm starting
to get these royalty checks.

65
00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:02.272
Look at all of those. You're rich.

66
00:03:02.440 --> 00:03:04.158
No. each one is for like 12 cents.

67
00:03:04.320 --> 00:03:06.754
It's barely worth the pain
in my hand to sign them.

68
00:03:13.680 --> 00:03:15.238
Jerry. you need any new furniture?

69
00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:17.152
- Why?
- Elaine's new boyfriend. you know...

70
00:03:17.320 --> 00:03:19.436
...he's giving me
this oversized chest of drawers.

71
00:03:19.600 --> 00:03:21.636
- It's a Farbman.
- He's giving you furniture?

72
00:03:21.800 --> 00:03:24.473
- Who is this guy?
- Who are any of her losers?

73
00:03:24.640 --> 00:03:26.358
You're on that list.

74
00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:29.958
I gotta go home and open up
the house for the carpet cleaners.

75
00:03:30.120 --> 00:03:32.111
You know. they're doing
my whole place for $25?

76
00:03:32.280 --> 00:03:35.158
Oh. no. no. no.
Not the Sunshine Carpet Cleaners?

77
00:03:35.320 --> 00:03:37.914
- Yeah. You heard of them?
- They're a crazy religious cult.

78
00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:41.755
The carpet cleaning is just a means
for them to get into your apartment.

79
00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:45.117
So? For a $25 cleaning. I can listen
to some pointless blather.

80
00:03:45.280 --> 00:03:47.589
I do it. I'm not even
getting the cleaning.

81
00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:50.910
I signed over 100 checks
this morning.

82
00:03:51.080 --> 00:03:53.719
- Hello. $12.
- Excuse me.

83
00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:55.518
Would you take a picture. please.

84
00:03:55.680 --> 00:03:57.318
Oh. yeah. Sure.

85
00:03:58.840 --> 00:04:00.432
I'm gonna ask this guy something.

86
00:04:03.960 --> 00:04:06.155
Hey. nice twirl you got there.

87
00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:08.038
You know who invented that.
don't you?

88
00:04:08.200 --> 00:04:10.156
- Hey. are you folks from Japan?
- Yes.

89
00:04:10.360 --> 00:04:11.952
You recognize that mug?

90
00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:13.792
That's the funny face
that greets you...

91
00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:16.190
...at the beginning of
The Super Terrific Happy Hour.

92
00:04:16.360 --> 00:04:18.794
- Oh. Super Terrific!
- Yeah.

93
00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:20.757
Yeah. huh? Yeah. that's him.

94
00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:22.428
What is he doing?

95
00:04:22.800 --> 00:04:25.792
Well. I don't know.
but something super-terrific. I'm sure.

96
00:04:25.960 --> 00:04:27.757
- That's funny.
- Oh. yeah. very funny.

97
00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:31.196
And it wouldn't be impolite
to laugh at his antics.

98
00:04:33.080 --> 00:04:36.356
Yeah. that's it. Because everybody
laughs at Jerry here in America.

99
00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:43.313
We're pretty much finished.

100
00:04:44.360 --> 00:04:45.634
There's just one more thing.

101
00:04:45.800 --> 00:04:47.711
Here it comes.

102
00:04:50.280 --> 00:04:52.748
You forgot to sign your check.

103
00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:56.073
Sorry.

104
00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:01.393
You sure there isn't anything else?

105
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:03.558
No.

106
00:05:04.800 --> 00:05:06.631
So that's it?

107
00:05:06.800 --> 00:05:10.315
- Unless you need a receipt.
- I wish that was all I needed.

108
00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:11.754
Life can be so confusing.

109
00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:13.717
I'm searching
for answers anywhere.

110
00:05:13.880 --> 00:05:15.552
Good luck with that.

111
00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:22.837
Hey.

112
00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:26.754
- What's with the claw?
- Super-terrific carpal tunnel syndrome.

113
00:05:27.080 --> 00:05:29.389
- There's no sign of Kramer.
- Oh. Brett.

114
00:05:29.560 --> 00:05:31.232
- This is Jerry.
- Hi.

115
00:05:31.840 --> 00:05:34.513
That's very funny. Elaine told me
you're some kind of comedian.

116
00:05:34.680 --> 00:05:36.511
I'm one kind.

117
00:05:37.320 --> 00:05:39.709
Have you seen the chest of drawers
Brett gave to Kramer?

118
00:05:39.880 --> 00:05:42.189
- Fleckman. Right.
- Farbman.

119
00:05:42.840 --> 00:05:45.479
- You gotta see them. They're beautiful.
- I'm sure they are.

120
00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:48.473
I'd be happy to get you some.
if that's what you're driving at.

121
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:52.117
- No. I'm fine. Thank you.
- Don't worry. It's no charge to you.

122
00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:55.556
Looks like what you really need is
a decent desk for writing your skits.

123
00:05:55.720 --> 00:05:57.119
I don't write skits.

124
00:05:57.280 --> 00:05:59.714
Of course you don't.
You don't have a proper workstation.

125
00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:01.393
I'll fax over my catalogue.

126
00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:07.389
Brett. Jerry doesn't have
a fax machine.

127
00:06:10.240 --> 00:06:12.151
I'm sure things will pick up
for you soon.

128
00:06:13.720 --> 00:06:15.358
Elaine. maybe we should get going.

129
00:06:15.520 --> 00:06:17.715
- Wanna join us?
- Where you going. the coffee shop?

130
00:06:17.880 --> 00:06:21.236
The coffee shop? I think we can
do a little better than that.

131
00:06:21.400 --> 00:06:24.358
You look like you could use
a solid meal at a real restaurant.

132
00:06:24.800 --> 00:06:27.553
- You look like you could use a...
- Jerry.

133
00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:33.954
Three hundred dollars. Mr. Oh. how
much would these run you in Tokyo?

134
00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:37.077
Those are 30.000 yen.

135
00:06:37.240 --> 00:06:39.037
Thirty thousand?

136
00:06:39.200 --> 00:06:41.555
Well. these are practically free.

137
00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:45.431
Giddy up. You're a cowboy now.

138
00:06:47.960 --> 00:06:49.951
I feel terrible about
your friend Jerry.

139
00:06:50.120 --> 00:06:52.350
He's upset that I gave Kramer
that chest of drawers.

140
00:06:52.520 --> 00:06:53.873
Why do you think he's upset?

141
00:06:54.040 --> 00:06:57.191
Well. how could he not be? Living in
that cramped little apartment...

142
00:06:57.360 --> 00:07:01.399
...that outdated furniture.
so terribly un-Karl-Farbman-like.

143
00:07:01.560 --> 00:07:05.633
We're not gonna talk about
Karl Farbman all night. are we?

144
00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:07.358
I hope not.

145
00:07:11.120 --> 00:07:13.953
Brett. is everything all right?

146
00:07:14.560 --> 00:07:16.118
What is it?
Is there someone outside?

147
00:07:16.480 --> 00:07:17.799
Elaine. the song.

148
00:07:21.800 --> 00:07:23.950
For a minute. I thought
it was that urban legend...

149
00:07:24.120 --> 00:07:26.111
...about the guy with the hook
hanging on the...

150
00:07:26.280 --> 00:07:28.953
Elaine. could you just not talk
for one minute?

151
00:07:30.080 --> 00:07:31.559
Sorry.

152
00:07:37.440 --> 00:07:38.998
- No spiel?
- Not a peep.

153
00:07:39.160 --> 00:07:40.912
They just cleaned the carpets
and left.

154
00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:43.036
They call themselves a cult.

155
00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:46.199
So you're angry
that this bizarre carpet cabal...

156
00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:47.793
...made no attempt to abduct you?

157
00:07:47.960 --> 00:07:49.632
They could have at least tried.

158
00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.594
Maybe they thought you looked
too smart to be brainwashed.

159
00:07:52.760 --> 00:07:54.398
- Please.
- Too dumb?

160
00:07:56.360 --> 00:08:00.672
Well. Mackie's back in town.
Nice duds.

161
00:08:01.440 --> 00:08:03.431
Yeah. it's a gift
from my Japanese friends.

162
00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:05.238
They're known as gift-givers.

163
00:08:05.400 --> 00:08:07.960
And tonight. we're going dancing
at the Rainbow Room.

164
00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:10.476
Sounds like you're throwing
their money around.

165
00:08:10.640 --> 00:08:12.596
Well. Jerry. they're Japanese.

166
00:08:12.760 --> 00:08:15.035
I mean. that TV you watch.
that sushi you eat...

167
00:08:15.200 --> 00:08:16.519
...even that kimono you wear...

168
00:08:16.680 --> 00:08:18.875
...where do you think
all that money goes?

169
00:08:19.240 --> 00:08:20.958
That's right.

170
00:08:21.120 --> 00:08:22.553
How'd you hook up with
these guys?

171
00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:25.188
They recognized Jerry from
The Super Terrific Happy Hour.

172
00:08:25.360 --> 00:08:27.396
See. you should be doing
your own show in Japan.

173
00:08:27.560 --> 00:08:28.754
Now. they get you.

174
00:08:28.920 --> 00:08:30.638
What kind of show am I gonna do
in Japan?

175
00:08:30.800 --> 00:08:32.597
What did you do with
that pilot you did?

176
00:08:32.760 --> 00:08:34.591
Yeah. the pilot.

177
00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:36.591
Right. That had
marvellous production values.

178
00:08:36.760 --> 00:08:38.671
I do a lot of business with
Japanese TV.

179
00:08:38.840 --> 00:08:40.637
They broadcast
a lot of American baseball.

180
00:08:40.800 --> 00:08:42.438
They got an office here
in New York.

181
00:08:42.600 --> 00:08:45.319
Forget it. The pilot was awful.
It failed.

182
00:08:45.480 --> 00:08:48.040
It failed here. Because here
every time you turn on a TV...

183
00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:51.078
...all you see is four morons
sitting around an apartment...

184
00:08:51.240 --> 00:08:52.673
...whining about their dates.

185
00:08:52.840 --> 00:08:55.957
See. George is right. Jerry.
See. here you're just another apple.

186
00:08:56.120 --> 00:09:01.319
But in Japan. you're an exotic fruit.
like an orange. which is rare there.

187
00:09:05.240 --> 00:09:06.434
You had a date?

188
00:09:06.600 --> 00:09:09.831
You went out with my butler? Who
said you could go out with my butler?

189
00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:13.788
- Why do I need your permission?
- Because he's my butler.

190
00:09:17.400 --> 00:09:20.631
So. what do you think?

191
00:09:20.800 --> 00:09:22.791
We're a bit confused.

192
00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:25.952
Why was this man Jerry's butler?

193
00:09:26.640 --> 00:09:29.279
You see. the man
who is the butler...

194
00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:32.352
...had gotten into
a car accident with Jerry.

195
00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:35.193
And because he didn't have
any insurance...

196
00:09:35.360 --> 00:09:39.478
...the judge decreed that
the man become Jerry's butler.

197
00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:42.074
Is this customary in
your legal system?

198
00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:46.274
No. That's what makes it
such a humorous situation.

199
00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:54.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

200
00:09:56.040 --> 00:10:00.352
I'm sorry. I'm sure Mr. Seinfeld is
very funny to Americans.

201
00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:04.991
But I'm not sure this butler show
would work in Japan.

202
00:10:05.160 --> 00:10:06.798
Oh. l... I disagree.

203
00:10:06.960 --> 00:10:09.872
You've... You've been living
in America too long.

204
00:10:10.040 --> 00:10:13.953
You've forgotten what it's like
to have no oranges.

205
00:10:19.040 --> 00:10:20.678
Sorry. My hand is numb.

206
00:10:20.840 --> 00:10:25.630
Yes. from endorsing checks for
The Super Terrific Happy Hour.

207
00:10:25.800 --> 00:10:28.314
You must go.

208
00:10:33.160 --> 00:10:34.912
Well. I think
I'm on the outs with Brett.

209
00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:37.636
I got shushed during "Desperado."

210
00:10:38.400 --> 00:10:40.834
What does he listen to.
the all "Desperado" station?

211
00:10:41.480 --> 00:10:44.677
He is just in his own world
when he hears that song.

212
00:10:44.840 --> 00:10:49.436
It's like I'm sitting there in the car.
and he's out riding fences.

213
00:10:49.600 --> 00:10:51.716
You know. what you need is
a song you can share.

214
00:10:52.280 --> 00:10:56.159
Yeah. you're right.
We need to find our song.

215
00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:59.232
Okay. So is there any song
that you feel very strongly about?

216
00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:03.348
I like "Witchy Woman."

217
00:11:03.520 --> 00:11:06.114
- "Witchy Woman"?
- You know. "Witchy Woman."

218
00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:10.433
Oh. "Witchy Woman."

219
00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:13.434
- Hey. Elaine.
- Hey.

220
00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:15.158
Hey. how was the Rainbow Room?

221
00:11:15.320 --> 00:11:16.719
Well. we... We had to leave early.

222
00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:20.998
There was a slight monetary
discrepancy regarding the bill.

223
00:11:21.160 --> 00:11:23.879
- Listen. could I borrow some pillows?
- What for?

224
00:11:24.040 --> 00:11:26.759
Well. my Japanese friends
are gonna stay with me.

225
00:11:26.920 --> 00:11:28.990
I thought they all had suites
at the Plaza.

226
00:11:29.440 --> 00:11:33.956
Well. I'm sorry. Jerry. We all don't
have checks rolling in like you do.

227
00:11:34.120 --> 00:11:37.317
Well. what about all that money
from the kimonos I wear?

228
00:11:38.160 --> 00:11:39.513
Well. they ran out of it.

229
00:11:39.680 --> 00:11:43.389
I mean. Manhattan can be quite
pricey. even with 50.000 yen.

230
00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:47.030
Fifty thousand yen?
Isn't that only a few hundred dollars?

231
00:11:47.400 --> 00:11:49.038
Evidently.

232
00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:53.158
Oh. by the way. tell Brett that
his chest of drawers are a big hit.

233
00:11:53.320 --> 00:11:55.470
My guests are
very comfortable in them.

234
00:11:55.800 --> 00:11:57.358
In them?

235
00:11:58.520 --> 00:12:00.795
You have them sleeping in drawers?

236
00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.231
Jerry. have you ever seen
the business hotels in Tokyo?

237
00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:07.312
They sleep in tiny.
stacked cubicles all the time.

238
00:12:07.480 --> 00:12:10.358
- They feel right at home.
- This has international incident...

239
00:12:10.520 --> 00:12:12.829
...written all over it.
- Oh. yeah. yeah.

240
00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:19.998
- Good night. Mr. Tanaka.
- Good night.

241
00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:22.720
- Good night. Mr. Oh.
- Good night.

242
00:12:23.640 --> 00:12:25.835
Good night. Mr. Yamaguchi.

243
00:12:37.080 --> 00:12:39.230
- What is this?
- Rice Krispies.

244
00:12:39.400 --> 00:12:40.799
East meets West. Jerry.

245
00:12:41.840 --> 00:12:44.957
That's a lovely little
bureau-and-breakfast you're running.

246
00:12:45.120 --> 00:12:46.348
Well. I'm off to the bank.

247
00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:53.719
Elaine. l...

248
00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:55.479
What do you think?

249
00:12:57.200 --> 00:12:58.474
What are you doing?

250
00:12:58.640 --> 00:13:01.154
That's "Witchy Woman."
I thought it could be our song.

251
00:13:01.880 --> 00:13:04.678
"Witchy Woman" is okay for you.
but I've already got a song.

252
00:13:05.240 --> 00:13:07.071
Oh. well. then how about
"Desperado"?

253
00:13:07.240 --> 00:13:08.514
We can share it.

254
00:13:08.720 --> 00:13:11.109
No. It's mine.

255
00:13:15.080 --> 00:13:18.390
Here you go.
Snap. crackle and pop.

256
00:13:22.440 --> 00:13:26.194
Good morning. Mr. Oh.
I gotta make up the drawer.

257
00:13:26.360 --> 00:13:28.635
Come back in half-hour.

258
00:13:36.200 --> 00:13:38.873
- Hey. I'll take one.
- Well. look who's back.

259
00:13:39.040 --> 00:13:42.271
Teddy. this is the guy says
he invented the twirl.

260
00:13:42.640 --> 00:13:44.312
Jerry Seinfeld.

261
00:13:44.480 --> 00:13:46.710
Teddy Padilac. long time. no see.

262
00:13:46.880 --> 00:13:48.472
What do you got
in a push-button mini?

263
00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:51.632
Same thing we had when
you bailed on us 15 years ago.

264
00:13:51.800 --> 00:13:54.598
Bailed? Come on. you knew
I wanted to be a comedian.

265
00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:57.797
Besides. we had some good times.
Remember Tropical Storm Renee?

266
00:13:57.960 --> 00:14:01.032
Oh. yeah. sure. But where were you
during the poncho craze of '84?

267
00:14:01.200 --> 00:14:02.838
I almost lost my house.

268
00:14:03.480 --> 00:14:04.993
Umbrella. buddy?

269
00:14:05.160 --> 00:14:07.913
Now we got that damn
urban sombrero to contend with.

270
00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:09.274
Easy. Clicky.

271
00:14:09.440 --> 00:14:11.351
I hear you're taking credit
for the twirl.

272
00:14:11.520 --> 00:14:13.636
Oh. it's so many years ago.
Who cares?

273
00:14:13.800 --> 00:14:16.268
I care. Clicky cares.

274
00:14:16.440 --> 00:14:19.876
- Look. could I just buy an umbrella?
- Yeah. sure.

275
00:14:20.040 --> 00:14:21.792
- Two hundred dollars.
- What?

276
00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:24.520
Special price for a real
foul-weather friend.

277
00:14:29.040 --> 00:14:31.634
Hey. George. All right.
how about that tour. huh?

278
00:14:31.800 --> 00:14:33.631
These guys are ready to
run the bases.

279
00:14:33.800 --> 00:14:37.076
Kramer. it's... It's raining.
They got the tarp on the field.

280
00:14:38.040 --> 00:14:40.395
Listen. George. what else
can I do with these guys?

281
00:14:40.560 --> 00:14:42.676
Bear in mind.
they're a little light on the yen.

282
00:14:44.080 --> 00:14:46.435
Well. l... I got the pilot
of the Jerry show.

283
00:14:46.640 --> 00:14:49.108
That's perfect.
How would you guys like to watch...

284
00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:52.113
...the Super Terrific Happy star.
Jerry Seinfeld?

285
00:14:52.280 --> 00:14:54.430
But we are also very hungry.

286
00:14:54.600 --> 00:14:57.194
Oh. yeah. yeah. Well. you guys
just watch the tape...

287
00:14:57.360 --> 00:14:58.873
...and I'll get you some food.

288
00:14:59.040 --> 00:15:00.871
- Go ahead. Yeah.
- Please.

289
00:15:01.040 --> 00:15:03.031
Hey. peanuts!

290
00:15:03.480 --> 00:15:05.471
George. George. got a minute?

291
00:15:05.680 --> 00:15:07.796
George. did you call some
carpet cleaners?

292
00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.070
- Are they here?
- They're in my office right now.

293
00:15:10.240 --> 00:15:12.515
- They haven't said anything to you?
- About what?

294
00:15:12.680 --> 00:15:15.069
What kind of a snobby.
stuck-up cult is this?

295
00:15:22.120 --> 00:15:25.271
- Hey. Jerry.
- Oh. hi. Brett.

296
00:15:25.440 --> 00:15:27.032
Haven't you ever
heard of an umbrella?

297
00:15:27.200 --> 00:15:28.838
I didn't have enough money.

298
00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:32.357
- Sure things will pick up for you.
- No. it's not that. It's...

299
00:15:34.320 --> 00:15:38.108
Oh. no. Look at the checks.
Hours of hard work ruined.

300
00:15:38.280 --> 00:15:41.317
Don't worry.
I can spot you the 12 cents.

301
00:15:41.480 --> 00:15:42.674
No. It's not the money.

302
00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:45.752
It's my hand.
It's crippled from writing and writing.

303
00:15:45.920 --> 00:15:47.478
Nothing's working for you. is it?

304
00:15:47.640 --> 00:15:49.073
Not at the moment. Brett.

305
00:15:49.240 --> 00:15:51.629
I'd give you a ride.
but I got Karl Farbman here.

306
00:15:52.960 --> 00:15:54.598
Thanks for stopping.

307
00:15:56.320 --> 00:15:59.312
Brett said you ran away from him
as if he were the boogity man?

308
00:15:59.480 --> 00:16:00.674
Bogeyman.

309
00:16:01.880 --> 00:16:04.030
- Boogie?
- I'm quite sure.

310
00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:07.396
Anyway. any luck
getting together on a song?

311
00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:10.120
No. He blew out my
"Witchy Woman."

312
00:16:10.280 --> 00:16:11.872
And he won't share "Desperado."

313
00:16:12.040 --> 00:16:13.871
Hey. what do you think of
"Oye Como Va"?

314
00:16:15.080 --> 00:16:17.753
Well. I'm running out of guys
here in this city. Jer.

315
00:16:20.560 --> 00:16:22.118
Hey. great news.

316
00:16:22.280 --> 00:16:25.636
I showed the pilot to Kramer's
Japanese friends. They loved it!

317
00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:27.677
Really? They bought
the butler character?

318
00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:30.434
Did I tell you that story's relatable?
That was a great show.

319
00:16:30.600 --> 00:16:32.636
That is why I'm bringing it
back to NBC.

320
00:16:32.800 --> 00:16:34.995
- NBC?
- Nakahama Broadcast Corporation.

321
00:16:37.480 --> 00:16:39.550
But they told us we must go now.

322
00:16:39.720 --> 00:16:42.154
Yeah. but now I have
my own market research.

323
00:16:42.320 --> 00:16:44.834
Actual Japanese viewers
that loved the show.

324
00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:47.309
- I'm gonna talk to Kramer.
- Hey. George. do me a favour.

325
00:16:47.480 --> 00:16:50.597
If they make you an offer.
whatever it is. just take it.

326
00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:56.310
Hey. by the way
what'd you think of Miss Yoshimura?

327
00:16:56.480 --> 00:16:58.038
- Who?
- The network executive.

328
00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:00.111
Do you think she liked me?

329
00:17:10.480 --> 00:17:12.391
Hey. look at who's here!

330
00:17:12.560 --> 00:17:14.437
George. come on in. Come on.

331
00:17:14.600 --> 00:17:16.716
- I want you to come in here.
- Come on in. fat boy!

332
00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:19.872
Get a good night's sleep.
all right. fellas? Big day tomorrow.

333
00:17:20.480 --> 00:17:21.959
All right.

334
00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:29.678
Last one.

335
00:17:35.200 --> 00:17:36.952
Here you are.

336
00:17:37.560 --> 00:17:39.471
- Where's the boys?
- No. I let them sleep in.

337
00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:41.949
I'm on my way to cash in
their plane tickets for them.

338
00:17:42.120 --> 00:17:43.553
They need a little food money.

339
00:17:43.720 --> 00:17:46.757
- The meeting starts in 10 minutes.
- Well. I set their alarm.

340
00:17:46.920 --> 00:17:49.309
But they did have a lot of sake
in that hot tub.

341
00:17:49.640 --> 00:17:51.039
I'm calling Jerry.

342
00:17:55.240 --> 00:17:56.434
- Yeah?
- Jerry!

343
00:17:56.600 --> 00:17:58.272
The Japanese guys had sake
in the hot tub.

344
00:17:58.440 --> 00:17:59.793
You gotta get them down here...

345
00:17:59.960 --> 00:18:02.428
...or I don't have a focus group
to sell the pilot.

346
00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:05.069
Uncle Leo?

347
00:18:05.240 --> 00:18:06.434
Jerry!

348
00:18:07.360 --> 00:18:09.794
All right. all right. I'll wake them up.

349
00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:12.279
Testy.

350
00:18:15.640 --> 00:18:17.039
Hello?

351
00:18:17.200 --> 00:18:21.671
- Mr. Jerry. open the drawer. please.
- It's stuck.

352
00:18:22.760 --> 00:18:25.035
The steam from the hot tub
must have warped the wood.

353
00:18:25.200 --> 00:18:26.918
- Pull harder.
- I'm trying.

354
00:18:27.080 --> 00:18:29.878
I can't get a grip.
My hand's had kind of a bad week.

355
00:18:30.040 --> 00:18:31.871
Very funny. But no joking. please.

356
00:18:32.400 --> 00:18:33.719
Don't worry. I'll get you out.

357
00:18:34.480 --> 00:18:36.710
Brett. believe me.
you don't have to do this.

358
00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:38.757
Elaine. I know he'll appreciate this.

359
00:18:38.920 --> 00:18:41.480
It's not as nice
as Kramer's cabinets. but it's a start.

360
00:18:41.640 --> 00:18:45.349
Well. I promise you. Jerry is not
jealous of Kramer's cabinets.

361
00:18:45.520 --> 00:18:47.670
Move to the back of the drawers!

362
00:18:47.840 --> 00:18:49.478
Jerry?

363
00:18:49.960 --> 00:18:51.234
Jerry.

364
00:18:51.680 --> 00:18:54.114
Not the Farbman!

365
00:19:19.240 --> 00:19:22.198
So. gentlemen. we have a deal?

366
00:19:33.960 --> 00:19:37.077
Excuse me. Did you hire
the Sunshine Carpet Cleaners?

367
00:19:37.280 --> 00:19:42.149
Yes. To clean up the coffee stain
left by Jerry Seinfeld.

368
00:19:45.360 --> 00:19:50.115
Mr... Mr. Wilhelm. what?
What are you doing here?

369
00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:52.356
I'm here to clean the carpets.

370
00:19:52.520 --> 00:19:57.594
Most of the world is carpeted.
and one day. we will do the cleaning.

371
00:20:00.800 --> 00:20:02.279
Him. you brainwashed?

372
00:20:02.440 --> 00:20:03.873
What's he got that I don't have?

373
00:20:06.360 --> 00:20:07.952
Mr. Wilhelm. you've been abducted.

374
00:20:08.120 --> 00:20:09.792
Mr. Wilhelm. you gotta listen to me.

375
00:20:09.960 --> 00:20:11.552
Wilhelm?

376
00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:15.520
My name is Tanya.

377
00:20:31.560 --> 00:20:33.391
Brett. I'm... I'm really sorry.

378
00:20:33.600 --> 00:20:36.831
I didn't mean to hit you
in the head with an axe.

379
00:20:38.440 --> 00:20:40.431
At least it was just a handle.

380
00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:42.279
Those beautiful cabinets.

381
00:20:42.840 --> 00:20:44.592
What am I gonna tell...?

382
00:20:44.920 --> 00:20:47.354
- I can't remember his name.
- Fleckman?

383
00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:48.794
Calm down. Brett. Okay?

384
00:20:48.960 --> 00:20:52.430
You could have a concussion.
Calm down.

385
00:21:13.080 --> 00:21:15.799
- His pulse is fine.
- Looks like a minor concussion.

386
00:21:15.960 --> 00:21:18.952
Let me see what I can do
to relieve the swelling.

387
00:21:21.840 --> 00:21:23.558
Doctor?

388
00:21:24.800 --> 00:21:26.199
Doctor?

389
00:21:27.240 --> 00:21:28.958
Doctor?

390
00:21:30.800 --> 00:21:33.473
Doctor. I think we're losing him.

391
00:21:34.305 --> 00:22:34.802
